    "analysis": "From prior steps we computed global thresholds and identified consecutive anomaly sequences (length >=2). The sequence-frequency analysis clearly shows two dominant anomaly clusters with start timestamps 1615514400 (32 sequences) and 1615516140 (31 sequences) — these map to ~10:00 and ~10:29–10:30. The top sequences that start at 1615514400 are mostly Tomcat Request/Processing metrics with anomaly_type=low (simultaneous drops across Tomcat02/03/04), while the 1615516140 cluster contains many short anomalies across IG, Redis, Mysql, apache and Tomcat metrics (mostly high-type tiny breaches). According to the fault-localization rules, we must now determine, for each of the two clusters, which component(s) first exhibited faults (and whether they are service-level or gateway-level) and which faulty component is the most-downstream faulty service in call traces. The sequence-level table we already created contains individual sequences for both timestamps, but we need a compact per-component summary for each of the two timestamps (counts, max severity, and top KPIs involved) to decide the root cause component and prepare for final trace/log confirmation. Error logs are empty so logs gave modest signals (Tomcat log.row_count and gc_pause hints) but not direct errors. We are not yet confident to declare final root causes.",
